The Poet having thus exhauſted imagination as well as mythology, in the deſcription of puniſhments for the diſturbers of mankind and foes to their country, raiſes his concluſion to a height of horror beyond the reach of expreſſion—
"Had I a hundred mouths, a hundred tongues,
"A voice of braſs, and adamantine lungs;
"Not half the mighty ſcene could I diſcloſe;
"Repeat their 〈…〉 their dreadful woes.
Nor has Virgil ſtrayed any farther through the fields of fancy or fable in this place, than to borrow ſtrength of colouring for the garb of truth; and I ſuſpect, that he drank from a purer fountain than that of Helicon, when he peopled his Tartarus with the ancient ſcourges of the human race. An authority ſacred among chriſtians has indeed given us a moſt awful confirmation of his doctrine.
